WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Today is Tuesday, September 22, 2011. My name is Joe Maniere of the Southern World History Program in the University of North Carolina.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:32.000
I'm at Chapel Hill. I'm a videographer, John Bishop in Washington, DC at the Jefferson Building of the Library of Congress to record an old history of you for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:46.000
We are really honored and privileged today to have with us Miss Doris and Ladner.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Dory.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
And Dr. Joyce Ladner, sister's worship and Mississippi who have had.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Joyce Ann as well.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Joyce Ann as well.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Long long history of involvement in progressive struggle and movement.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And let me know as well where to land and have a whiskey lane, Nichols, who is the project career at the museum.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And I think you're not one of the people who has to give you a drink or not work to have a glass of tea car.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Okay. Miss Ladner, Dr. Ladner, thank you so much for coming in and sitting down to the bridge and...

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Thank you.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Thank you.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
You've sent me the challenge of opening with a complicated or stimulating question.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
I thought I might...

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
We can work back for this.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.000
But let me take you back since we're sitting here on the mall in Washington DC.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Let me take you back to it.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
I might have seen some decree.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:48.000
And I want to ask about the March, but most particularly, I want to ask about the ambivalence in the range of thought and feeling criticism that you had about that experience,

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
because I know it was a complicated question.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Well, my feelings were one of ambivalence and complicated in that there were so many things going on in the front line,

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
meaning that Medgevus had been killed on June 12th.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.000
This funeral was June 16th.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And Lars Giyat had been beaten, Miss Fannie Lou Hamer had been jailed and beaten very badly in Wai'anone, Mississippi.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.000
And there was a bus boycott going...

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Not a bus boycott, but a boycott of all the stores in Jackson, Mississippi.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
And people were being arrested in Greenwood, Mississippi.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.000
We were under siege.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So we knew that we had to return back to these homes.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.000
We had three guys on death row in Georgia.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So coming together was good to address...

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Bring out grievances to the seat of government to let the president and everybody know.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:55.000
But we knew that we had to return back to those towns and what would be waiting for us.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:02.000
I really looked forward to coming here and to letting everybody know what was going on.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:10.000
But in reality, James Farmer, who was the executive director of Corps, was in jail in Placman, Paris, Louisiana, he couldn't attend.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:18.000
So my sister, Joace, worked in the Marchion Washington office coordinating the transportation to working out the logistics.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And I was working in the SNCC office raising money for the organization's lablihood and also recruiting people to participate in the same march.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:43.000
But the point was I was always thinking about what was going on because I'm a frontline person and always thinking about the strategy.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
And my sister was talking about the fun we had and I was thinking about the other side of it.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:58.000
And I said, one to say that death shall have no dominion over what we were doing at the same time because we didn't fear death as well as enjoying ourselves partying and so forth.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
We were young and zealots.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:03.000
We were zealots.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So in essence, the one thing that bothered us was that we didn't see, which always kept us going and when they wanted to change John's speech.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:29.000
But I'll let Joace talk about that because she was involved back there with Portland and Jim and so forth.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
But that was one thing that turned us off.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
And we were always busy.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
We had all this energy.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Energy.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
19, 20 years old, you're very energetic.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Very busy.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:58.000
I was at a conference, student conference, and Lake Forest, Illinois, the day that MegaEvers was killed.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And I had gone there as a SNCC representative to try to recruit students and also to raise money and to spread generally spread the word about the Southern movement.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:21.000
And I got a call while I was at this conference one evening from Rubidara's Robinson and Rubidys said,

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Joace, MegaEvers has been killed.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And I said, oh my god, I've got to go home.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
We've got to get back to Jackson.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And she said, no, you need to go to Washington to work on the Marchion Washington.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
I said, yeah, but I've known MegaEvers since I was 14.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
I mean, I was very upset.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
I think I was even crying.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
I'm sure I was.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And she said, but we need to send two representatives from SNCC to work on the March.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And I want you to go from there, from get you an airline ticket.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And I want you to go to New York City for the rest of the summer to work on the Marchion.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:09.000
And she said, this is, I remember so clearly, this is what Meg would have expected of you.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
I wanted you to do one of the others, she said.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:19.000
And I was like, taking a bag, but I always had the ability to think with my head,

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
even in difficult emotional times.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:26.000
So I saw the logic of what she could, and why could appeal to my logic,

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
so she appealed to that part of me.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And so I was then off to New York to work at the Harlem headquarters for Marchion Washington.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:43.000
And I spent the summer there working under Biod Rustin's direction.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:50.000
There were, we, Dorianna State with Rachelle Hart, who was a young person,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:57.000
and she lived at, was 8th Avenue in 24th Street in the ILGW Condo Apartments.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
And she had one bedroom apartment there.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:06.000
Dorianna slept on the sofa, and then later in the summer, Ellen Holmes arrived.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And she was at Yale Law School, and she came, and she joined us up at the Marchion Quarters.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.000
So Dorianna was working out at the SNCC office for Rachelle Eleanor,

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.000
and I worked up in the Harlem office at the March.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And my job really was to raise money.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:30.000
So I went, I don't know, I went out, I went out to Jersey, around the city,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:36.000
spreading the word about the March, and why it was so important to bring people

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
who were involved in the movement from the South to participate in the March.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:47.000
So Rachelle used to say that every time Joyce went out to be a lawyer,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:54.000
she went out to raise money, she came back with enough to run another bus.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And that was what was important to us.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:04.000
We worked long hours, we worked on Saturday, it was very tiring.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
One Saturday I remember seeing Malcolm X for the first time.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:16.000
He used to speak on Coenah 125th Street, and stopped and listened to him speak.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:21.000
And as I said, we worked very long hours, we did whatever Biot told us to do.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:26.000
So it was well organized.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:34.000
Very well organized, he was a great organizer, he had a very clear tactical sense.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And he saw the big picture and he, you know, anything he asked us to do, we did.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:47.000
But he also left us with enough flexibility, you know, to be independent and go out there

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
and do what had to be done.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:56.000
So every night, we worked late at night, came into back to the apartment.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:01.000
And there was Bobbie Dylan sitting on the sofa, strumming his guitar,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
and I wanted to go to sleep.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And he would sit there at the midnight, and I just couldn't wait until he got asleep.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
He was sitting there, entertaining, enduring.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:18.000
And, you know, he was well known, but we were all young people at the time.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:23.000
I didn't see him as a great, you know, famous person, I think.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
We were peers in a way.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And then we went down to Washington for the march, the day before.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And we stayed at what was then called the Statli-Hilton Hotel.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
It's now 16 things, say.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Right, it's the Washington, not Washington, but the Hilton.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:52.000
I'm not sure what the official name of that hotel is, but it was, back then it was called the Statli-Hilton.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
And it was the March Hotel.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:02.000
And I remember, there were a lot of media people, a lot of people who were there for the march.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:10.000
And I remember meeting Malcolm X, seeing him rather in the lobby after the march.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
And I'm pretty sure I saw him there before the march occurred as well.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
No, we'd saw him the morning after we'd pick it to the Justice Department.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
Yeah, early that morning we went down to pick it to the Justice Department.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:29.000
Because of Don Harris, John Prado and John Prado.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:34.000
We were in jail in America's Georgia.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:38.000
And they were jailed for sedition.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
Essentially what they were doing was trying to organize.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.000
And that was the charge that were pledged charge.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
That was the tremendous charge.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
Because they could have been killed.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And we had petitioned the federal government to no avail.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So we picked it up about six o'clock that morning.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Then we got read it earlier, went on over to the mall for the march.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:07.000
And I had a pass, a stage pass because that was on the staff.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And so what I remember first was seeing all those people.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
It was an incredible sight.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:19.000
19-year-old from Mississippi who had never seen huge numbers.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
In fact, no one on that platform had seen numbers like that before.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
But I remember seeing people of Mark coming and coming and coming.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
And they just kept coming.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And then I saw the people on stage.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
And I think I might have been impressed by some of them.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:41.000
But I think probably most about Josephine Baker.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
She was the person I remembered most.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
And I mean, because she was a legend.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And I could not imagine that I would have ever met her.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
Very grearious and exotic looking.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:57.000
And she was shaking everyone's hand, hugging people and so on.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:04.000
And then seeing the actors, people in movies up there.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:10.000
And that was even though there were people who were very strong supporters of SNCC,

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:15.000
who raised a lot of money for us.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:20.000
And then seeing the union guys on stage.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
In seeing the Haley Ajax and then hearing her sing.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
In other words, it was just kind of across the swath of a lot of people,

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
you know, who are the swath of America on that stage.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
I remember seeing Marlon Brando.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And I used to, I felt, I got the kind of chills when I saw him and Josephine Baker.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:44.000
And I was thinking more than anything else that I support really ran deep, you know.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:50.000
That was what I felt.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And I saw Lena Horn.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:58.000
And I met her earlier in the summer because she came to Jackson, Mississippi,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:03.000
at the request of maybe it was before he was killed.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:08.000
But we also, I met her at the Delta Sigma Theta Convention at summer in New York

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:14.000
when John Trump Power, who was later my roommate at Tuvalu,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:19.000
and Joyce Barrett, who worked with SNCC in Southwest Georgia,

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
and I, we were all Delta's.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
There were two white girls who were Delta members of Delta Sigma Theta.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And we were all in the movement.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:32.000
So Jean Noble, who was the Delta Sigma Theta president at the time,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:37.000
and was from Albany, Georgia, and Professor at the time at Brooklyn College.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.000
Later at NYU, invited us to speak about what was happening in the South.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And the Delta's were very activist oriented.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:55.000
And they used to bail other Delta's young Delta sorrows out of jail in the South.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:01.000
And so we spoke about, at the convention, about what was happening.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:07.000
And Lena Horne talked about having been down in Jackson.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And she had a very, very strong, deep emotional tie to the movement.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:13.000
Very unusual.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
She felt it in her soul.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.000
Look, Lexus.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Her mother had, according to her biography, her mother had taken her to Georgia,

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
her natural mother, because she was reared by her grandmother, her father's mother,

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
had taken her to Georgia.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
And she stayed for a long period of time.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:33.000
And she so identified with that area, because she never lost her southern accent.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:38.000
And Bill is straight horned, was also with her and her son.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:46.000
And I remember being at a house there in Jackson with Dr. Noble president of Delta,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
Lena Horne, Dick Gregory.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
And I'm not sure who has made it.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
Ebbers was there.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And they were all talking.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:59.000
And here I'm like 2019 and 20 years old sitting there observing them.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:05.000
And the one thing about Lena Horne was that when Joyce and I were on the platform

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:11.000
at the Lincoln Memorial, the French television wanted to interview her.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
She said, no, these are the young people you should interview.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
She said, she said, she's have to be interviewed.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:22.000
And she took me by the hand and took me over to the, I think it was NBC,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:30.000
that NASA Dickerson, the legendary female reporter, television news person,

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:35.000
was upon a scaffold and we climbed up the scaffold and she told her interview this young person,

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.000
because young woman, because she lives in the south and she knows what it's like.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
So she was very generous in that regard.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And I remember being interviewed and when I got back home,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:51.000
we later to this Hattiesburg, my mother said, I saw you on TV.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And that was like, so this is 1963.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.000
You remember 50 years, almost 50 years ago.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And it was television wasn't what it is now.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So it was so strange.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
And mother said, yeah, all the neighbors, she said, Ms. Katie saw you.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
And Ms. Adder saw you.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
She went on all the neighbors who had seen me as well.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
And my younger sisters and brothers said as well.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:24.000
And that made, my mother was a low-key, no nonsense, strong will,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:29.000
very strong will and kind of shy, but she liked me.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:33.000
Right, right, just the opposite of me.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:40.000
And she would give you a lot of compliments, but when she gave you one,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.000
she said, well, you look nice up there.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
And I said, thank you, mother.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
And that meant everything because, and she had had a lot of ambivalence

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.000
about our involvement in the movement because she was afraid that,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
number one, something could happen to us.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:59.000
And also she always worried that the house would be burned down by the clan.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:03.000
But mother started off teaching us, let me go back to how we,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.000
it all started when we were very young.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
And then when we were talking with her telling us to always look white men

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
and eyes when you're talking to them, and don't blink, never look down.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
And we were like four and five years old.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And she grew up in an integrated community in Wayne County, Mississippi.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:28.000
And so she really should have checked the way she saw people.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And she would never fear anyone.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.000
So she always told us to know we was good as anybody.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:38.000
That was the mantra that passed through five generations of our family,

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:43.000
a maternal line of our family, and we can go back in a minute and talk about that.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:50.000
But mother, she was, while she had ambivalence and some fear and

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
trepidation about our involvement, but always remember that she never told us not to go.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
And that was important.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
She never said, stay here, never.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:05.000
So when I remember on that day, being interviewed by French media reporter

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:11.000
and then NASA Dickerson at NBC.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:18.000
And so it was, but what I remembered most was John Lewis' speech.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:24.000
Because I was on the podium with Cortland, Mildred and Jim Foreman.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:33.000
And John, there were others around, but that small core group of people

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:37.000
was when John was saying, well, I don't want to change anything.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.000
I don't want to.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:43.000
And he wasn't screaming at the shouting because he's soft-poken.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And Jim was saying, well, they should be telling us what to do.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And of course, as words spread out in the crowd to the snake people,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:58.000
everybody got very upset because this was our speech and what we felt most of all

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.000
was that this archbishop doesn't know what we go through.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
Who is he, what right, an authority?

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
And we always challenged authority.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:10.000
Who gave him the right to decide what John should say.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:15.000
And it was a crisis on the platform for a while.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:21.000
And finally, the language was changed as little as possible.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.000
And he gave the speech.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:30.000
But that was that and the guy, our friends being in jail in America's Georgia

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
were the defining things I remember most that I remembered now about the march.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:40.000
Of course, I remember King's speech, but we had an ambivalent relationship with King as well.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:48.000
We called, referred to him as the law, D-E-L-A-W-D, like the Lord.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:52.000
And everybody's looking up to him when, in fact,

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:57.000
the snake people went into the most dangerous areas, like Albany and places.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
And we called it breaking an area.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
Staying there under the toughest conditions until you finally have a breakthrough

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:07.000
with a local community when they begin to let you stay with them.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:15.000
Then you begin to, they come out to the meetings and they start getting involved in organizing as well.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:19.000
And then it builds up to a crisis stage and that's when King would come in.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:20.000
We felt.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:23.000
And so we had an ambivalent relationship with him.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:24.000
We respected him, of course.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
But it wasn't all, oh, this is a fantastic man.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
This is a great speechy gate.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.000
Because that wasn't it.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.000
The reality was that we knew we were leaving that next day.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:40.000
I left the next morning with John Lewis on a flight back to Atlanta.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:46.000
Funny which you remember, I remember the plane was in the back of the airline.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:53.000
There was a round seating area, like a circular sofa back there.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:57.000
And John and I were sitting back there.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:04.000
And we went to the SNCC office and I went back there because I was waiting for a ride back

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:11.000
to Hattisburg because a week later I was going back to Tugeloo for my senior year.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:14.000
How did you get back in a car?

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
But did you go back to New York first?

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.000
No, I went to Hattis to Jackson.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Well, John, I guess it was because I was given a plane ticket because I had been on the staff to get back south.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
Otherwise I would have been in the car as well.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:36.000
And then what I remember is that I don't remember riding a high euphoria either.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:43.000
I'm not sure that I'm, of course, a time and events reshaped memory.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:50.000
But I don't recall having seen that as something that I savored and carried with me.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:56.000
Because we couldn't for long because we were right back in that same tough environment.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:07.000
Three weeks later we got on the bus and Bob Moses drove a school bus to Birmingham.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:17.000
And he took a dozen of more SNCC workers to the funeral of the three little girls who had been murdered.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:24.000
So I always saw that as, okay, back in your face you had your big marks but we were back in control, you know, the white races.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:29.000
So we didn't have time to savor things, the march or anything else.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:38.000
It was a big event and also when as young people you don't hold on to things there are some more living to do right after that.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:40.000
So that was what I remembered most.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:43.000
But I remember the contradiction in my mind.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.000
There's always people there.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:50.000
And then we had now had a funeral of the most vulnerable people of all.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
And they hadn't killed children before.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:56.000
And that was another big thing that stuck out of my mind.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:08.000
I remember writing a, a, a, a, a, a, a, a, I'm sorry, a, a, a, a, a, a, a, a, a, a, a, the first being very upset about a child being killed.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:11.000
Because we so identified with him.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:13.000
Yeah. He was our age.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.000
And right.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:25.600
And in the throws of out of adolescent, adolescence, and here's a boy and the feeling was if they

00:23:25.600 --> 00:23:27.440
could do that to him, they could kill my brothers.

00:23:27.440 --> 00:23:31.400
I never thought that they would kill me, but I always felt they would kill me.

00:23:31.400 --> 00:23:33.400
I felt they would kill my brothers.

00:23:33.400 --> 00:23:34.400
Very deeply.

00:23:34.400 --> 00:23:41.400
I remember I don't need to work to drink.

00:23:41.400 --> 00:23:53.200
Remember that summer in matches when you were ill so frequently I understand because of

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:55.200
the pressure on them.

00:23:55.200 --> 00:23:57.200
Yes, the stress.

00:23:57.200 --> 00:24:04.200
I would go to sleep at night or not expecting to wake up.

00:24:04.200 --> 00:24:11.920
Yes, and it was unusual because I've never seen a telephone that would ring in your hand

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:14.800
and it's off the hook.

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:21.640
And literally holding the phone, take the phone off the hook, the receiver and it's still

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:27.720
ringing because people in the south go to bed very early and the phone would start ringing

00:24:27.720 --> 00:24:34.080
probably between 6'3rd and 7th and they would leave their phones off the hook so we had

00:24:34.080 --> 00:24:40.440
no contact with the outside world and we would live right beside an alley.

00:24:40.440 --> 00:24:48.640
So we never knew whether or not we were going to wake up and I developed stomach problems

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:57.600
from eating, it was pure stress, pure stress, but it made me more determined.

00:24:57.600 --> 00:25:08.000
So determined one time that I went to Mr. Charles Evers had guns maybe close to 80 people arrested

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:14.760
and they would take an apartment in a tentry and I never followed him because I didn't

00:25:14.760 --> 00:25:16.960
think that he was respected.

00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:18.760
I didn't respect him.

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:22.640
So we were trying to get the bond signed.

00:25:22.640 --> 00:25:27.760
You needed two signatures, the chief of police and you needed a property owner.

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:32.160
And so I got so frustrated because we were in a delta, we had to travel from Nat just

00:25:32.160 --> 00:25:37.960
which is in the far south to the Mississippi Delta which is probably 200 miles to get people

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:39.960
out.

00:25:39.960 --> 00:25:44.920
I asked one of the police officers where is the chief of police and he said he's at the

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:46.160
holiday in.

00:25:46.160 --> 00:25:51.960
So I got a cab and went to the holiday in which was segregated and stood and had him

00:25:51.960 --> 00:25:52.960
paid.

00:25:52.960 --> 00:25:58.160
I was at the cashier's desk and had him paid standing in the middle of the floor.

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:01.560
I was that frustrated and that angry.

00:26:01.560 --> 00:26:03.320
And so he never responded.

00:26:03.320 --> 00:26:07.080
I don't know what he would have done if he had confronted me.

00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:08.360
I don't know.

00:26:08.360 --> 00:26:13.000
But that was the height of level of frustration that one would get to.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.000
I got in the cab and went back to the house.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:24.120
And another time I remember getting very frustrated was the next day after it was killed.

00:26:24.120 --> 00:26:28.120
We went to the Masonic Temple.

00:26:28.120 --> 00:26:38.320
Dave Dennis from CORE, his wife, Maddie Bivens, who was our cousin and myself went to the

00:26:38.320 --> 00:26:41.040
Masonic Temple.

00:26:41.040 --> 00:26:47.680
And there were two white police officers sitting on motorcycles and I ran up to the MSS

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:49.800
to scream him.

00:26:49.800 --> 00:26:50.800
Where were you last night?

00:26:50.800 --> 00:26:52.560
Why are you here now?

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:53.560
Shoot, shoot, shoot.

00:26:53.560 --> 00:26:55.560
In the back like you did in Maddie Gabbard.

00:26:55.560 --> 00:26:56.560
Shoot, shoot, shoot.

00:26:56.560 --> 00:26:57.560
Just screaming.

00:26:57.560 --> 00:26:58.560
Just enraged.

00:26:58.560 --> 00:26:59.560
Enraged.

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:05.280
I had the amount of rage I can't even begin to describe.

00:27:05.280 --> 00:27:11.240
And it was anger, frustration, hurt, pain, all everything you could think of.

00:27:11.240 --> 00:27:13.960
And they sat there with their heads bowed.

00:27:13.960 --> 00:27:22.520
And only recently have I begun to think that they practiced non-violence with me because

00:27:22.520 --> 00:27:23.520
they never responded.

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:25.960
They think they were upset about the killing.

00:27:25.960 --> 00:27:26.960
They never responded.

00:27:26.960 --> 00:27:29.320
They could have turned around and shot me.

00:27:29.320 --> 00:27:31.400
I know, but do you think they made it possible?

00:27:31.400 --> 00:27:37.160
The insight is beginning to come to me as I get old and think that they looked sorrowful

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:38.160
themselves.

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:39.160
They had their heads down.

00:27:39.160 --> 00:27:40.160
They never glared at me.

00:27:40.160 --> 00:27:41.160
They never looked at me.

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:45.280
They never made any towards me gestures.

00:27:45.280 --> 00:27:47.160
They just sat there.

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:50.920
And I was really enraged.

00:27:50.920 --> 00:27:56.720
And it only came to me recently that they were using the same tactics, non-violence tactics,

00:27:56.720 --> 00:27:59.560
passive resistance, with me that we used this in.

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:02.000
They probably felt bad about it.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:05.400
Well, I might have struck that little core of the men into the man.

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:10.640
Well, as you keep living as mother, you say the more you live, the longer you live, the

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:11.920
more you learn.

00:28:11.920 --> 00:28:13.080
And this is coming to me.

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:16.600
These revelations are coming to me that that was what was practiced.

00:28:16.600 --> 00:28:21.760
Because I've been told recently that a lot of whites in the South and in Jackson, in

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:24.760
particular, did not care for that.

00:28:24.760 --> 00:28:28.560
Well, I went to both trials and up for mega.

00:28:28.560 --> 00:28:30.720
And the first trial was all right.

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:34.280
Although I had to kick some white men's feet because they put their feet up on the bench

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:38.600
and wouldn't let me sit down and I kick the foot and told them moving, then sat down.

00:28:38.600 --> 00:28:41.280
That's the type of temper I had.

00:28:41.280 --> 00:28:44.480
The judge told me to sit in and where they wanted to prevent it.

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:51.200
So the next trial, when the government came in, they made that goal up to the balcony with

00:28:51.200 --> 00:28:56.680
a cane behind my head, the sheriff, a big thick cane.

00:28:56.680 --> 00:29:02.320
And the mist trial happened so quickly until we didn't know we had gotten caught.

00:29:02.320 --> 00:29:07.960
And only divine intervention happened at that particular time because we were caught

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:13.600
between the courthouse and the police station and the black street, the Far East street was

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:14.600
quite a distance.

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:19.280
And we were trying to figure out how are we going to get away from this mob.

00:29:19.280 --> 00:29:23.360
And who would drive up at one Jess and Morris?

00:29:23.360 --> 00:29:26.240
He said, do you all need a ride?

00:29:26.240 --> 00:29:30.360
And we hopped in that Volkswagen bus and took off.

00:29:30.360 --> 00:29:33.320
These are the kind of things that happen.

00:29:33.320 --> 00:29:39.640
And that's why we are alive because there was a greater power than us that was looking

00:29:39.640 --> 00:29:40.640
after all of us.

00:29:40.640 --> 00:29:43.680
I said my serendipity.

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:52.480
But I remember seeing Ross Barnett walk into the trial of meckers, killers.

00:29:52.480 --> 00:30:02.400
And I just, he went over and shook the hand.

00:30:02.400 --> 00:30:04.040
And he was no different.

00:30:04.040 --> 00:30:11.480
He was indistinguishable from the other clan supporters sitting there.

00:30:11.480 --> 00:30:13.480
And I said, my God, there's.

00:30:13.840 --> 00:30:19.560
Another time during that, we were going to go to Barnett's inauguration.

00:30:19.560 --> 00:30:27.720
Why are you on that meckers trial each day when Beckwood would come in.

00:30:27.720 --> 00:30:31.720
The clan would stand up and give him a standing ovation and a float and a float.

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:32.720
And he would bow.

00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:37.480
Yeah, I mean, he was, and it was like some famous long-starred.

00:30:37.480 --> 00:30:43.440
And the district attorney said, choosing a jury, Medgev was a nigger.

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:44.680
He lived over a nigger town.

00:30:44.680 --> 00:30:46.000
I didn't agree with what he did.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:47.120
And I know you don't either.

00:30:47.120 --> 00:30:49.040
But it's my job to uphold the law.

00:30:49.040 --> 00:30:52.320
Do you think it's wrong for a white man to kill a nigger?

00:30:52.320 --> 00:30:55.480
And that's the way the jury was selected.

00:30:55.480 --> 00:30:56.480
That's what Will and Wallace said.

00:30:56.480 --> 00:30:57.480
Yes.

00:30:57.480 --> 00:30:58.480
Yeah.

00:30:58.480 --> 00:30:59.480
Did the D.A.

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:00.480
Yeah.

00:31:00.480 --> 00:31:02.480
That's Paul from the district.

00:31:02.480 --> 00:31:03.480
More right.

00:31:03.480 --> 00:31:05.480
Just like, I don't mean to.

00:31:05.480 --> 00:31:06.480
Of course.

00:31:06.480 --> 00:31:11.480
I'm interested in this because it's one of so many indications of how extreme distress

00:31:11.480 --> 00:31:17.480
and pressure was even on young and very energetic, as you said, all the young people.

00:31:17.480 --> 00:31:23.480
I've read that you even were physically ill so many nights in matches because of the

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:25.480
It was a stomach.

00:31:25.480 --> 00:31:30.960
And also eating greasy foods, the fried food.

00:31:30.960 --> 00:31:31.960
We ate it.

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:36.280
What was called a White House restaurant that was owned by some sisters who were independent,

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:38.200
lots of land.

00:31:38.200 --> 00:31:45.120
And every time I would eat the food would come up, fried chicken.

00:31:45.120 --> 00:31:50.120
And now to this day I've watched my diet, I can't eat fried foods.

00:31:50.120 --> 00:31:52.440
And this is hereditary I would have made.

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:59.760
I used to worry about her because I was often the safety of graduate school.

00:31:59.760 --> 00:32:07.120
And I was, I lived with so much guilt, just tremendous guilt.

00:32:07.120 --> 00:32:12.680
And I was worried my sister was still back in the South, but not only in the South, but

00:32:12.680 --> 00:32:18.680
in the natures, she had the most notorious reputation for it being a dangerous place.

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:23.960
And we kept in touch by phone and I started working on her telling her it was time for her

00:32:23.960 --> 00:32:27.960
to leave to come to get away.

00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:28.960
And eventually she did.

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:31.120
She moved to St. Louis with me.

00:32:31.120 --> 00:32:32.120
But.

00:32:32.120 --> 00:32:34.120
You don't feel the because you had to be a nurse.

00:32:34.120 --> 00:32:37.520
Because I left because I left and went to graduate school.

00:32:37.520 --> 00:32:41.080
I felt that I wouldn't have changed anything.

00:32:41.080 --> 00:32:46.240
But so living with guilt.

00:32:46.240 --> 00:32:50.480
But at the same time feeling that you did what was best for you, it was the worst combination

00:32:50.480 --> 00:32:51.480
in the world.

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:53.560
I didn't see it that way.

00:32:53.560 --> 00:32:54.560
But I did.

00:32:54.560 --> 00:33:02.920
I saw what I was doing is something that I had to do that I had to make some changes.

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:05.640
And the line was drawn in the scene.

00:33:05.640 --> 00:33:14.160
And I had to cross the line and I had to go for it because I did not want to live under

00:33:14.160 --> 00:33:16.680
the condition that had come before me.

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:19.240
And I didn't want to leave the conditions that way.

00:33:19.240 --> 00:33:22.360
So it's a passion with me.

00:33:22.360 --> 00:33:28.880
I think all of us felt that what drove us was that we felt the one that we were doing

00:33:28.880 --> 00:33:30.840
the right thing.

00:33:30.840 --> 00:33:38.560
We never questioned whether or not the cause was not a just one.

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:42.080
That was a foreground conclusion.

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:50.080
But I think my sister endured a lot more dangerous situations by far than I did.

00:33:50.080 --> 00:33:57.360
But at the same time, I mean I was in enough dangerous situations.

00:33:57.360 --> 00:34:03.560
But I always felt that I was always scared.

00:34:03.560 --> 00:34:06.560
And I didn't want to be around people in the movement who.

00:34:06.560 --> 00:34:08.560
But so I'm not scared, you know.

00:34:08.560 --> 00:34:11.120
Because especially if they were northerners.

00:34:11.120 --> 00:34:17.760
Because they could get you killed very easily because they didn't have respect for the

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:19.680
local traditions.

00:34:19.680 --> 00:34:24.240
And because we sawderners knew what those conditions were.

00:34:24.240 --> 00:34:30.640
We could decode them a lot quicker and easier, more easily than the northerners.

00:34:30.640 --> 00:34:34.600
A lot of times they acted out of ignorance.

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:40.160
But because my roommate Joan Trump, I seen you a year or two glue, for example, used

00:34:40.160 --> 00:34:41.160
to.

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:44.760
I don't care about these people, they're not going to do anything to me.

00:34:44.760 --> 00:34:47.040
And I said, well, you're not going to get me killed.

00:34:47.040 --> 00:34:51.760
I used to carry around a black scarf in my pocket.

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:58.720
And when we were driving back to Tugulu College at night, on this long stretch of road called

00:34:58.720 --> 00:35:01.680
Hanging Mouth Road, there were no lights.

00:35:01.680 --> 00:35:05.480
And Tugulu was eight miles from downtown Jackson.

00:35:05.480 --> 00:35:08.480
So we had a, I used to put her on the floor.

00:35:08.480 --> 00:35:11.360
And if she were going on the floor, I said we got to put this scarf on because your

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:15.160
long blonde hair is not going to get me killed.

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:19.080
And because you know, people will just shot at us, even if they just know we movement

00:35:19.080 --> 00:35:20.080
workers.

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:22.720
And we were, there were no whites in the car.

00:35:22.720 --> 00:35:31.760
But I came to understand, I guess, as I got older, that fear doesn't mean inaction.

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:42.000
I mean, courage was the ability to act or to prevail in spite of one's fear.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:46.000
Because you could easily be paralyzed by your fear.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.720
And if you, you know, my mind was constantly working.

00:35:48.720 --> 00:35:53.880
I was sitting there, I remember once, Lawrence Giyat told me in a snake meeting, he said,

00:35:53.880 --> 00:35:58.960
joy, if we listen to you, you know, you take everything to a logical conclusion.

00:35:58.960 --> 00:35:59.960
We would do anything.

00:35:59.960 --> 00:36:01.320
That's what I didn't mean it that way.

00:36:01.320 --> 00:36:05.280
I was just trying to point, you know, because my mind is always working on this hand, on

00:36:05.280 --> 00:36:08.880
that hand, that out of these, this is what would happen on one side of it, this would

00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:09.880
happen on another.

00:36:09.880 --> 00:36:12.280
That's what I didn't mean not to do it.

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:16.280
I was just thinking about what could happen.

00:36:16.280 --> 00:36:21.920
Could I take you back for just a minute to a very specific material service, answer

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:22.920
question?

00:36:22.920 --> 00:36:25.720
Could you describe the home you grew up in, in the home or should I say?

00:36:25.720 --> 00:36:26.720
The what?

00:36:26.720 --> 00:36:27.720
The home.

00:36:27.720 --> 00:36:28.720
The home.

00:36:28.720 --> 00:36:30.960
Maybe the, what it looked like, just like in the very environment.

00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:33.320
Our home, our, our every home.

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:41.240
It was, we had three bedrooms, living room, dining room, kitchen.

00:36:41.240 --> 00:36:43.240
Those were the covering on the house.

